  version: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 51ee3e37f5ded7941ab6216610f6fc67, type: 2}
  description: 
  chapters:
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Daniel in Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s Court"
      title: "Daniel in Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s Court"
      number: 1
      content: "  During the third year of King Jehoiakim\u2019s reign in Judah,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        King Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon came to Jerusalem and besieged it. "
      comments:
      - number: '1:1 '
        content: "This event occurred in 605 <span class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>,
          during the third year of Jehoiakim\u2019s reign (according to the calendar
          system in which the new year begins in the spring)."
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'The Lord gave him victory over King Jehoiakim of Judah and permitted
        him to take some of the sacred objects from the Temple of God. So Nebuchadnezzar
        took them back to the land of Babylonia[[COMMENT(0)]] and placed them in
        the treasure-house of his god.  '
      comments:
      - number: '1:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the land of Shinar.</b>
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Then the king ordered Ashpenaz, his chief of staff, to bring to the
        palace some of the young men of Judah\u2019s royal family and other noble
        families, who had been brought to Babylon as captives. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "\u201CSelect only strong, healthy, and good-looking young men,\u201D
        he said. \u201CMake sure they are well versed in every branch of learning,
        are gifted with knowledge and good judgment, and are suited to serve in the
        royal palace. Train these young men in the language and literature of Babylon.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '1:4 '
        content: Or <b>of the Chaldeans.</b>
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'The king assigned them a daily ration of food and wine from his own
        kitchens. They were to be trained for three years, and then they would enter
        the royal service.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'Daniel, Hananiah, Mishael, and Azariah were four of the young men
        chosen, all from the tribe of Judah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'The chief of staff renamed them with these Babylonian names:Daniel
        was called Belteshazzar.Hananiah was called Shadrach.Mishael was called Meshach.Azariah
        was called Abednego.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'But Daniel was determined not to defile himself by eating the food
        and wine given to them by the king. He asked the chief of staff for permission
        not to eat these unacceptable foods. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Now God had given the chief of staff both respect and affection for
        Daniel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "But he responded, \u201CI am afraid of my lord the king, who has
        ordered that you eat this food and wine. If you become pale and thin compared
        to the other youths your age, I am afraid the king will have me beheaded.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'Daniel spoke with the attendant who had been appointed by the chief
        of staff to look after Daniel, Hananiah, Mishael, and Azariah. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "\u201CPlease test us for ten days on a diet of vegetables and water,\u201D
        Daniel said. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CAt the end of the ten days, see how we look compared to the
        other young men who are eating the king\u2019s food. Then make your decision
        in light of what you see.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "The attendant agreed to Daniel\u2019s suggestion and tested them
        for ten days.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'At the end of the ten days, Daniel and his three friends looked healthier
        and better nourished than the young men who had been eating the food assigned
        by the king. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'So after that, the attendant fed them only vegetables instead of
        the food and wine provided for the others.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'God gave these four young men an unusual aptitude for understanding
        every aspect of literature and wisdom. And God gave Daniel the special ability
        to interpret the meanings of visions and dreams.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'When the training period ordered by the king was completed, the chief
        of staff brought all the young men to King Nebuchadnezzar. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'The king talked with them, and no one impressed him as much as Daniel,
        Hananiah, Mishael, and Azariah. So they entered the royal service. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Whenever the king consulted them in any matter requiring wisdom and
        balanced judgment, he found them ten times more capable than any of the magicians
        and enchanters in his entire kingdom.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: Daniel remained in the royal service until the first year of the reign
        of King Cyrus.[[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: '1:21 '
        content: Cyrus began his reign (over Babylon) in 539 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s Dream"
      title: "Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s Dream"
      number: 1
      content: "  One night during the second year of his reign,[[COMMENT(0)]] Nebuchadnezzar
        had such disturbing dreams that he couldn\u2019t sleep. "
      comments:
      - number: '2:1 '
        content: "The second year of Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s reign was 603 <span class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>"
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'He called in his magicians, enchanters, sorcerers, and astrologers,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and he demanded that they tell him what he had dreamed. As they stood before
        the king, '
      comments:
      - number: '2:2 '
        content: Or <b>Chaldeans; </b>also in 2:4, 5, 10.
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "he said, \u201CI have had a dream that deeply troubles me, and I
        must know what it means.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Then the astrologers answered the king in Aramaic,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        \u201CLong live the king! Tell us the dream, and we will tell you what it
        means.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '2:4 '
        content: The original text from this point through chapter 7 is in Aramaic.
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "But the king said to the astrologers, \u201CI am serious about this.
        If you don\u2019t tell me what my dream was and what it means, you will be
        torn limb from limb, and your houses will be turned into heaps of rubble! "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "But if you tell me what I dreamed and what the dream means, I will
        give you many wonderful gifts and honors. Just tell me the dream and what
        it means!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "They said again, \u201CPlease, Your Majesty. Tell us the dream, and
        we will tell you what it means.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "The king replied, \u201CI know what you are doing! You\u2019re stalling
        for time because you know I am serious when I say, "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u2018If you don\u2019t tell me the dream, you are doomed.\u2019
        So you have conspired to tell me lies, hoping I will change my mind. But
        tell me the dream, and then I\u2019ll know that you can tell me what it means.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "The astrologers replied to the king, \u201CNo one on earth can tell
        the king his dream! And no king, however great and powerful, has ever asked
        such a thing of any magician, enchanter, or astrologer! "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "The king\u2019s demand is impossible. No one except the gods can
        tell you your dream, and they do not live here among people.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'The king was furious when he heard this, and he ordered that all
        the wise men of Babylon be executed. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "And because of the king\u2019s decree, men were sent to find and
        kill Daniel and his friends.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "When Arioch, the commander of the king\u2019s guard, came to kill
        them, Daniel handled the situation with wisdom and discretion. "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "He asked Arioch, \u201CWhy has the king issued such a harsh decree?\u201D
        So Arioch told him all that had happened. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'Daniel went at once to see the king and requested more time to tell
        the king what the dream meant.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'Then Daniel went home and told his friends Hananiah, Mishael, and
        Azariah what had happened. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'He urged them to ask the God of heaven to show them his mercy by
        telling them the secret, so they would not be executed along with the other
        wise men of Babylon. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'That night the secret was revealed to Daniel in a vision. Then Daniel
        praised the God of heaven. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "He said,\u201CPraise the name of God forever and ever,for he has
        all wisdom and power.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'He controls the course of world events;he removes kings and sets
        up other kings.He gives wisdom to the wiseand knowledge to the scholars.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'He reveals deep and mysterious thingsand knows what lies hidden in
        darkness,though he is surrounded by light.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: Daniel Interprets the Dream'
      title: Daniel Interprets the Dream
      number: 23
      content: "I thank and praise you, God of my ancestors,for you have given me
        wisdom and strength.You have told me what we asked of youand revealed to
        us what the king demanded.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Then Daniel went in to see Arioch, whom the king had ordered to execute
        the wise men of Babylon. Daniel said to him, \u201CDon\u2019t kill the wise
        men. Take me to the king, and I will tell him the meaning of his dream.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Arioch quickly took Daniel to the king and said, \u201CI have found
        one of the captives from Judah who will tell the king the meaning of his
        dream!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "The king said to Daniel (also known as Belteshazzar), \u201CIs this
        true? Can you tell me what my dream was and what it means?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Daniel replied, \u201CThere are no wise men, enchanters, magicians,
        or fortune-tellers who can reveal the king\u2019s secret. "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: 'But there is a God in heaven who reveals secrets, and he has shown
        King Nebuchadnezzar what will happen in the future. Now I will tell you your
        dream and the visions you saw as you lay on your bed.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "\u201CWhile Your Majesty was sleeping, you dreamed about coming events.
        He who reveals secrets has shown you what is going to happen. "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'And it is not because I am wiser than anyone else that I know the
        secret of your dream, but because God wants you to understand what was in
        your heart.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "\u201CIn your vision, Your Majesty, you saw standing before you a
        huge, shining statue of a man. It was a frightening sight. "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'The head of the statue was made of fine gold. Its chest and arms
        were silver, its belly and thighs were bronze, '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: 'its legs were iron, and its feet were a combination of iron and baked
        clay. '
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'As you watched, a rock was cut from a mountain,[[COMMENT(0)]] but
        not by human hands. It struck the feet of iron and clay, smashing them to
        bits. '
      comments:
      - number: '2:34 '
        content: As in Greek version (see also 2:45); Hebrew lacks <b>from a mountain.</b>
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'The whole statue was crushed into small pieces of iron, clay, bronze,
        silver, and gold. Then the wind blew them away without a trace, like chaff
        on a threshing floor. But the rock that knocked the statue down became a
        great mountain that covered the whole earth.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "\u201CThat was the dream. Now we will tell the king what it means. "
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: 'Your Majesty, you are the greatest of kings. The God of heaven has
        given you sovereignty, power, strength, and honor. '
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: 'He has made you the ruler over all the inhabited world and has put
        even the wild animals and birds under your control. You are the head of gold.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "\u201CBut after your kingdom comes to an end, another kingdom, inferior
        to yours, will rise to take your place. After that kingdom has fallen, yet
        a third kingdom, represented by bronze, will rise to rule the world. "
      comments: []
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: 'Following that kingdom, there will be a fourth one, as strong as
        iron. That kingdom will smash and crush all previous empires, just as iron
        smashes and crushes everything it strikes. '
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: 'The feet and toes you saw were a combination of iron and baked clay,
        showing that this kingdom will be divided. Like iron mixed with clay, it
        will have some of the strength of iron. '
      comments: []
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: 'But while some parts of it will be as strong as iron, other parts
        will be as weak as clay. '
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: 'This mixture of iron and clay also shows that these kingdoms will
        try to strengthen themselves by forming alliances with each other through
        intermarriage. But they will not hold together, just as iron and clay do
        not mix.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: "\u201CDuring the reigns of those kings, the God of heaven will set
        up a kingdom that will never be destroyed or conquered. It will crush all
        these kingdoms into nothingness, and it will stand forever. "
      comments: []
    - name: '45: Nebuchadnezzar Rewards Daniel'
      title: Nebuchadnezzar Rewards Daniel
      number: 45
      content: "That is the meaning of the rock cut from the mountain, though not
        by human hands, that crushed to pieces the statue of iron, bronze, clay,
        silver, and gold. The great God was showing the king what will happen in
        the future. The dream is true, and its meaning is certain.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '46: '
      title: 
      number: 46
      content: 'Then King Nebuchadnezzar threw himself down before Daniel and worshiped
        him, and he commanded his people to offer sacrifices and burn sweet incense
        before him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '47: '
      title: 
      number: 47
      content: "The king said to Daniel, \u201CTruly, your God is the greatest of
        gods, the Lord over kings, a revealer of mysteries, for you have been able
        to reveal this secret.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '48: '
      title: 
      number: 48
      content: 'Then the king appointed Daniel to a high position and gave him many
        valuable gifts. He made Daniel ruler over the whole province of Babylon,
        as well as chief over all his wise men. '
      comments: []
    - name: '49: '
      title: 
      number: 49
      content: "At Daniel\u2019s request, the king appointed Shadrach, Meshach, and
        Abednego to be in charge of all the affairs of the province of Babylon, while
        Daniel remained in the king\u2019s court."
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s Gold Statue"
      title: "Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s Gold Statue"
      number: 1
      content: '  King Nebuchadnezzar made a gold statue ninety feet tall and nine
        feet wide[[COMMENT(0)]] and set it up on the plain of Dura in the province
        of Babylon. '
      comments:
      - number: '3:1 '
        content: Aramaic <b>60 cubits </b>[27 meters] <b>tall and 6 cubits </b>[2.7
          meters] <b>wide.</b>
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Then he sent messages to the high officers, officials, governors,
        advisers, treasurers, judges, magistrates, and all the provincial officials
        to come to the dedication of the statue he had set up. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'So all these officials[[COMMENT(0)]] came and stood before the statue
        King Nebuchadnezzar had set up.  '
      comments:
      - number: '3:3 '
        content: Aramaic <b>the high officers, officials, governors, advisers, treasurers,
          judges, magistrates, and all the provincial officials.</b>
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Then a herald shouted out, \u201CPeople of all races and nations
        and languages, listen to the king\u2019s command! "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "When you hear the sound of the horn, flute, zither, lyre, harp, pipes,
        and other musical instruments,[[COMMENT(0)]] bow to the ground to worship
        King Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s gold statue. "
      comments:
      - number: '3:5 '
        content: The identification of some of these musical instruments is uncertain.
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Anyone who refuses to obey will immediately be thrown into a blazing
        furnace.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'So at the sound of the musical instruments,[[COMMENT(0)]] all the
        people, whatever their race or nation or language, bowed to the ground and
        worshiped the gold statue that King Nebuchadnezzar had set up.  '
      comments:
      - number: '3:7 '
        content: Aramaic <b>the horn, flute, zither, lyre, harp, and other musical
          instruments.</b>
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'But some of the astrologers[[COMMENT(0)]] went to the king and informed
        on the Jews. '
      comments:
      - number: '3:8 '
        content: Aramaic <b>Chaldeans.</b>
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "They said to King Nebuchadnezzar, \u201CLong live the king! "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'You issued a decree requiring all the people to bow down and worship
        the gold statue when they hear the sound of the horn, flute, zither, lyre,
        harp, pipes, and other musical instruments. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'That decree also states that those who refuse to obey must be thrown
        into a blazing furnace. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "But there are some Jews\u2014Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego\u2014whom
        you have put in charge of the province of Babylon. They pay no attention
        to you, Your Majesty. They refuse to serve your gods and do not worship the
        gold statue you have set up.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Then Nebuchadnezzar flew into a rage and ordered that Shadrach, Meshach,
        and Abednego be brought before him. When they were brought in, '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Nebuchadnezzar said to them, \u201CIs it true, Shadrach, Meshach,
        and Abednego, that you refuse to serve my gods or to worship the gold statue
        I have set up? "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "I will give you one more chance to bow down and worship the statue
        I have made when you hear the sound of the musical instruments.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        But if you refuse, you will be thrown immediately into the blazing furnace.
        And then what god will be able to rescue you from my power?\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:15 '
        content: Aramaic <b>the horn, flute, zither, lyre, harp, pipes, and other
          musical instruments.</b>
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego replied, \u201CO Nebuchadnezzar,
        we do not need to defend ourselves before you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'If we are thrown into the blazing furnace, the God whom we serve
        is able to save us. He will rescue us from your power, Your Majesty. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: The Blazing Furnace'
      title: The Blazing Furnace
      number: 18
      content: "But even if he doesn\u2019t, we want to make it clear to you, Your
        Majesty, that we will never serve your gods or worship the gold statue you
        have set up.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Nebuchadnezzar was so furious with Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego
        that his face became distorted with rage. He commanded that the furnace be
        heated seven times hotter than usual. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'Then he ordered some of the strongest men of his army to bind Shadrach,
        Meshach, and Abednego and throw them into the blazing furnace. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'So they tied them up and threw them into the furnace, fully dressed
        in their pants, turbans, robes, and other garments. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'And because the king, in his anger, had demanded such a hot fire
        in the furnace, the flames killed the soldiers as they threw the three men
        in. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'So Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, securely tied, fell into the
        roaring flames.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "But suddenly, Nebuchadnezzar jumped up in amazement and exclaimed
        to his advisers, \u201CDidn\u2019t we tie up three men and throw them into
        the furnace?\u201D\u201CYes, Your Majesty, we certainly did,\u201D they replied.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "\u201CLook!\u201D Nebuchadnezzar shouted. \u201CI see four men, unbound,
        walking around in the fire unharmed! And the fourth looks like a god[[COMMENT(0)]]!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:25 '
        content: Aramaic <b>like a son of the gods.</b>
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "Then Nebuchadnezzar came as close as he could to the door of the
        flaming furnace and shouted: \u201CShadrach, Meshach, and Abednego, servants
        of the Most High God, come out! Come here!\u201DSo Shadrach, Meshach, and
        Abednego stepped out of the fire. "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Then the high officers, officials, governors, and advisers crowded
        around them and saw that the fire had not touched them. Not a hair on their
        heads was singed, and their clothing was not scorched. They didn\u2019t even
        smell of smoke!  "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "Then Nebuchadnezzar said, \u201CPraise to the God of Shadrach, Meshach,
        and Abednego! He sent his angel to rescue his servants who trusted in him.
        They defied the king\u2019s command and were willing to die rather than serve
        or worship any god except their own God. "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "Therefore, I make this decree: If any people, whatever their race
        or nation or language, speak a word against the God of Shadrach, Meshach,
        and Abednego, they will be torn limb from limb, and their houses will be
        turned into heaps of rubble. There is no other god who can rescue like this!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: Then the king promoted Shadrach, Meshach, and Abednego to even higher
        positions in the province of Babylon.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s Dream about a Tree"
      title: "Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s Dream about a Tree"
      number: 1
      content: "    [[COMMENT(0)]]King Nebuchadnezzar sent this message to the people
        of every race and nation and language throughout the world:\u201CPeace and
        prosperity to you!  "
      comments:
      - number: '4:1 '
        content: '  Verses 4:1-3 are numbered 3:31-33 in Aramaic text.    '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CI want you all to know about the miraculous signs and wonders
        the Most High God has performed for me.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'How great are his signs,how powerful his wonders!His kingdom will
        last forever,his rule through all generations.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "  [[COMMENT(0)]]\u201CI, Nebuchadnezzar, was living in my palace
        in comfort and prosperity. "
      comments:
      - number: '4:4 '
        content: '  Verses 4:4-37 are numbered 4:1-34 in Aramaic text.  '
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'But one night I had a dream that frightened me; I saw visions that
        terrified me as I lay in my bed. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'So I issued an order calling in all the wise men of Babylon, so they
        could tell me what my dream meant. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'When all the magicians, enchanters, astrologers,[[COMMENT(0)]] and
        fortune-tellers came in, I told them the dream, but they could not tell me
        what it meant. '
      comments:
      - number: '4:7 '
        content: Or <b>Chaldeans.</b>
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'At last Daniel came in before me, and I told him the dream. (He was
        named Belteshazzar after my god, and the spirit of the holy gods is in him.)  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CI said to him, \u2018Belteshazzar, chief of the magicians,
        I know that the spirit of the holy gods is in you and that no mystery is
        too great for you to solve. Now tell me what my dream means.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "\u201C\u2018While I was lying in my bed, this is what I dreamed.
        I saw a large tree in the middle of the earth. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: 'The tree grew very tall and strong, reaching high into the heavens
        for all the world to see. '
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'It had fresh green leaves, and it was loaded with fruit for all to
        eat. Wild animals lived in its shade, and birds nested in its branches. All
        the world was fed from this tree.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201C\u2018Then as I lay there dreaming, I saw a messenger,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        a holy one, coming down from heaven. "
      comments:
      - number: '4:13 '
        content: Aramaic <b>a watcher; </b>also in 4:23.
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "The messenger shouted,\u201CCut down the tree and lop off its branches!Shake
        off its leaves and scatter its fruit!Chase the wild animals from its shadeand
        the birds from its branches.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'But leave the stump and the roots in the ground,bound with a band
        of iron and bronzeand surrounded by tender grass.Now let him be drenched
        with the dew of heaven,and let him live with the wild animals among the plants
        of the field.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'For seven periods of time,let him have the mind of a wild animalinstead
        of the mind of a human.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "For this has been decreed by the messengers[[COMMENT(0)]];it is commanded
        by the holy ones,so that everyone may knowthat the Most High rules over the
        kingdoms of the world.He gives them to anyone he chooses\u2014even to the
        lowliest of people.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '4:17 '
        content: Aramaic <b>the watchers.</b>
    - name: '18: Daniel Explains the Dream'
      title: Daniel Explains the Dream
      number: 18
      content: "\u201C\u2018Belteshazzar, that was the dream that I, King Nebuchadnezzar,
        had. Now tell me what it means, for none of the wise men of my kingdom can
        do so. But you can tell me because the spirit of the holy gods is in you.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201CUpon hearing this, Daniel (also known as Belteshazzar) was
        overcome for a time, frightened by the meaning of the dream. Then the king
        said to him, \u2018Belteshazzar, don\u2019t be alarmed by the dream and what
        it means.\u2019\u201CBelteshazzar replied, \u2018I wish the events foreshadowed
        in this dream would happen to your enemies, my lord, and not to you! "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'The tree you saw was growing very tall and strong, reaching high
        into the heavens for all the world to see. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'It had fresh green leaves and was loaded with fruit for all to eat.
        Wild animals lived in its shade, and birds nested in its branches. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'That tree, Your Majesty, is you. For you have grown strong and great;
        your greatness reaches up to heaven, and your rule to the ends of the earth.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "\u201C\u2018Then you saw a messenger, a holy one, coming down from
        heaven and saying, \u201CCut down the tree and destroy it. But leave the
        stump and the roots in the ground, bound with a band of iron and bronze and
        surrounded by tender grass. Let him be drenched with the dew of heaven. Let
        him live with the animals of the field for seven periods of time.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "\u201C\u2018This is what the dream means, Your Majesty, and what
        the Most High has declared will happen to my lord the king. "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'You will be driven from human society, and you will live in the fields
        with the wild animals. You will eat grass like a cow, and you will be drenched
        with the dew of heaven. Seven periods of time will pass while you live this
        way, until you learn that the Most High rules over the kingdoms of the world
        and gives them to anyone he chooses. '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'But the stump and roots of the tree were left in the ground. This
        means that you will receive your kingdom back again when you have learned
        that heaven rules.  '
      comments: []
    - name: "27: The Dream\u2019s Fulfillment"
      title: "The Dream\u2019s Fulfillment"
      number: 27
      content: "\u201C\u2018King Nebuchadnezzar, please accept my advice. Stop sinning
        and do what is right. Break from your wicked past and be merciful to the
        poor. Perhaps then you will continue to prosper.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "\u201CBut all these things did happen to King Nebuchadnezzar. "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: 'Twelve months later he was taking a walk on the flat roof of the
        royal palace in Babylon. '
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: "As he looked out across the city, he said, \u2018Look at this great
        city of Babylon! By my own mighty power, I have built this beautiful city
        as my royal residence to display my majestic splendor.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "\u201CWhile these words were still in his mouth, a voice called down
        from heaven, \u2018O King Nebuchadnezzar, this message is for you! You are
        no longer ruler of this kingdom. "
      comments: []
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: "You will be driven from human society. You will live in the fields
        with the wild animals, and you will eat grass like a cow. Seven periods of
        time will pass while you live this way, until you learn that the Most High
        rules over the kingdoms of the world and gives them to anyone he chooses.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '33: Nebuchadnezzar Praises God'
      title: Nebuchadnezzar Praises God
      number: 33
      content: "\u201CThat same hour the judgment was fulfilled, and Nebuchadnezzar
        was driven from human society. He ate grass like a cow, and he was drenched
        with the dew of heaven. He lived this way until his hair was as long as eagles\u2019
        feathers and his nails were like birds\u2019 claws.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: "\u201CAfter this time had passed, I, Nebuchadnezzar, looked up to
        heaven. My sanity returned, and I praised and worshiped the Most High and
        honored the one who lives forever.His rule is everlasting,and his kingdom
        is eternal.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: "All the people of the earthare nothing compared to him.He does as
        he pleasesamong the angels of heavenand among the people of the earth.No
        one can stop him or say to him,\u2018What do you mean by doing these things?\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "\u201CWhen my sanity returned to me, so did my honor and glory and
        kingdom. My advisers and nobles sought me out, and I was restored as head
        of my kingdom, with even greater honor than before.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: "\u201CNow I, Nebuchadnezzar, praise and glorify and honor the King
        of heaven. All his acts are just and true, and he is able to humble the proud.\u201D"
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Writing on the Wall'
      title: The Writing on the Wall
      number: 1
      content: '  Many years later King Belshazzar gave a great feast for 1,000 of
        his nobles, and he drank wine with them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'While Belshazzar was drinking the wine, he gave orders to bring in
        the gold and silver cups that his predecessor,[[COMMENT(0)]] Nebuchadnezzar,
        had taken from the Temple in Jerusalem. He wanted to drink from them with
        his nobles, his wives, and his concubines. '
      comments:
      - number: '5:2 '
        content: Aramaic <b>father; </b>also in 5:11, 13, 18.
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'So they brought these gold cups taken from the Temple, the house
        of God in Jerusalem, and the king and his nobles, his wives, and his concubines
        drank from them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'While they drank from them they praised their idols made of gold,
        silver, bronze, iron, wood, and stone.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Suddenly, they saw the fingers of a human hand writing on the plaster
        wall of the king\u2019s palace, near the lampstand. The king himself saw
        the hand as it wrote, "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'and his face turned pale with fright. His knees knocked together
        in fear and his legs gave way beneath him.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "The king shouted for the enchanters, astrologers,[[COMMENT(0)]] and
        fortune-tellers to be brought before him. He said to these wise men of Babylon,
        \u201CWhoever can read this writing and tell me what it means will be dressed
        in purple robes of royal honor and will have a gold chain placed around his
        neck. He will become the third highest ruler in the kingdom!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '5:7 '
        content: Or <b>Chaldeans; </b>also in 5:11.
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "But when all the king\u2019s wise men had come in, none of them could
        read the writing or tell him what it meant. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'So the king grew even more alarmed, and his face turned pale. His
        nobles, too, were shaken.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "But when the queen mother heard what was happening, she hurried to
        the banquet hall. She said to Belshazzar, \u201CLong live the king! Don\u2019t
        be so pale and frightened. "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "There is a man in your kingdom who has within him the spirit of the
        holy gods. During Nebuchadnezzar\u2019s reign, this man was found to have
        insight, understanding, and wisdom like that of the gods. Your predecessor,
        the king\u2014your predecessor King Nebuchadnezzar\u2014made him chief over
        all the magicians, enchanters, astrologers, and fortune-tellers of Babylon. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: Daniel Explains the Writing'
      title: Daniel Explains the Writing
      number: 12
      content: "This man Daniel, whom the king named Belteshazzar, has exceptional
        ability and is filled with divine knowledge and understanding. He can interpret
        dreams, explain riddles, and solve difficult problems. Call for Daniel, and
        he will tell you what the writing means.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "So Daniel was brought in before the king. The king asked him, \u201CAre
        you Daniel, one of the exiles brought from Judah by my predecessor, King
        Nebuchadnezzar? "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'I have heard that you have the spirit of the gods within you and
        that you are filled with insight, understanding, and wisdom. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'My wise men and enchanters have tried to read the words on the wall
        and tell me their meaning, but they cannot do it. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "I am told that you can give interpretations and solve difficult problems.
        If you can read these words and tell me their meaning, you will be clothed
        in purple robes of royal honor, and you will have a gold chain placed around
        your neck. You will become the third highest ruler in the kingdom.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "Daniel answered the king, \u201CKeep your gifts or give them to someone
        else, but I will tell you what the writing means. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Your Majesty, the Most High God gave sovereignty, majesty, glory,
        and honor to your predecessor, Nebuchadnezzar. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'He made him so great that people of all races and nations and languages
        trembled before him in fear. He killed those he wanted to kill and spared
        those he wanted to spare. He honored those he wanted to honor and disgraced
        those he wanted to disgrace. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'But when his heart and mind were puffed up with arrogance, he was
        brought down from his royal throne and stripped of his glory. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'He was driven from human society. He was given the mind of a wild
        animal, and he lived among the wild donkeys. He ate grass like a cow, and
        he was drenched with the dew of heaven, until he learned that the Most High
        God rules over the kingdoms of the world and appoints anyone he desires to
        rule over them.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "\u201CYou are his successor,[[COMMENT(0)]] O Belshazzar, and you
        knew all this, yet you have not humbled yourself. "
      comments:
      - number: '5:22 '
        content: 'Aramaic <b>son.</b>  '
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "For you have proudly defied the Lord of heaven and have had these
        cups from his Temple brought before you. You and your nobles and your wives
        and concubines have been drinking wine from them while praising gods of silver,
        gold, bronze, iron, wood, and stone\u2014gods that neither see nor hear nor
        know anything at all. But you have not honored the God who gives you the
        breath of life and controls your destiny! "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'So God has sent this hand to write this message.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "\u201CThis is the message that was written: Mene, Mene, Tekel, and
        Parsin. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "This is what these words mean:  Mene means \u2018numbered\u2019\u2014God
        has numbered the days of your reign and has brought it to an end.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "  Tekel means \u2018weighed\u2019\u2014you have been weighed on the
        balances and have not measured up.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "  Parsin  [[COMMENT(0)]] means \u2018divided\u2019\u2014your kingdom
        has been divided and given to the Medes and Persians.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '5:28 '
        content: '  Aramaic   <b>Peres, </b>  the singular of   <b>Parsin.</b>  '
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "Then at Belshazzar\u2019s command, Daniel was dressed in purple robes,
        a gold chain was hung around his neck, and he was proclaimed the third highest
        ruler in the kingdom.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'That very night Belshazzar, the Babylonian[[COMMENT(0)]] king, was
        killed.[[COMMENT(1)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '5:30a '
        content: Or <b>Chaldean.</b>
      - number: '5:30b '
        content: 'The Persians and Medes conquered Babylon in October 539 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>  '
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: '  [[COMMENT(0)]]And Darius the Mede took over the kingdom at the
        age of sixty-two.'
      comments:
      - number: '5:31 '
        content: '  Verse 5:31 is numbered 6:1 in Aramaic text.  '
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Daniel in the Lions\u2019 Den"
      title: "Daniel in the Lions\u2019 Den"
      number: 1
      content: '    [[COMMENT(0)]]Darius the Mede decided to divide the kingdom into
        120 provinces, and he appointed a high officer to rule over each province. '
      comments:
      - number: '6:1 '
        content: '  Verses 6:1-28 are numbered 6:2-29 in Aramaic text.  '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "The king also chose Daniel and two others as administrators to supervise
        the high officers and protect the king\u2019s interests. "
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "Daniel soon proved himself more capable than all the other administrators
        and high officers. Because of Daniel\u2019s great ability, the king made
        plans to place him over the entire empire.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "Then the other administrators and high officers began searching for
        some fault in the way Daniel was handling government affairs, but they couldn\u2019t
        find anything to criticize or condemn. He was faithful, always responsible,
        and completely trustworthy. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "So they concluded, \u201COur only chance of finding grounds for accusing
        Daniel will be in connection with the rules of his religion.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "So the administrators and high officers went to the king and said,
        \u201CLong live King Darius! "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "We are all in agreement\u2014we administrators, officials, high officers,
        advisers, and governors\u2014that the king should make a law that will be
        strictly enforced. Give orders that for the next thirty days any person who
        prays to anyone, divine or human\u2014except to you, Your Majesty\u2014will
        be thrown into the den of lions. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "And now, Your Majesty, issue and sign this law so it cannot be changed,
        an official law of the Medes and Persians that cannot be revoked.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'So King Darius signed the law.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'But when Daniel learned that the law had been signed, he went home
        and knelt down as usual in his upstairs room, with its windows open toward
        Jerusalem. He prayed three times a day, just as he had always done, giving
        thanks to his God. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "Then the officials went together to Daniel\u2019s house and found
        him praying and asking for God\u2019s help. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "So they went straight to the king and reminded him about his law.
        \u201CDid you not sign a law that for the next thirty days any person who
        prays to anyone, divine or human\u2014except to you, Your Majesty\u2014will
        be thrown into the den of lions?\u201D\u201CYes,\u201D the king replied,
        \u201Cthat decision stands; it is an official law of the Medes and Persians
        that cannot be revoked.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Then they told the king, \u201CThat man Daniel, one of the captives
        from Judah, is ignoring you and your law. He still prays to his God three
        times a day.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Hearing this, the king was deeply troubled, and he tried to think
        of a way to save Daniel. He spent the rest of the day looking for a way to
        get Daniel out of this predicament.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "In the evening the men went together to the king and said, \u201CYour
        Majesty, you know that according to the law of the Medes and the Persians,
        no law that the king signs can be changed.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "So at last the king gave orders for Daniel to be arrested and thrown
        into the den of lions. The king said to him, \u201CMay your God, whom you
        serve so faithfully, rescue you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'A stone was brought and placed over the mouth of the den. The king
        sealed the stone with his own royal seal and the seals of his nobles, so
        that no one could rescue Daniel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "Then the king returned to his palace and spent the night fasting.
        He refused his usual entertainment and couldn\u2019t sleep at all that night.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Very early the next morning, the king got up and hurried out to the
        lions\u2019 den. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "When he got there, he called out in anguish, \u201CDaniel, servant
        of the living God! Was your God, whom you serve so faithfully, able to rescue
        you from the lions?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "Daniel answered, \u201CLong live the king! "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "My God sent his angel to shut the lions\u2019 mouths so that they
        would not hurt me, for I have been found innocent in his sight. And I have
        not wronged you, Your Majesty.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'The king was overjoyed and ordered that Daniel be lifted from the
        den. Not a scratch was found on him, for he had trusted in his God.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Then the king gave orders to arrest the men who had maliciously accused
        Daniel. He had them thrown into the lions\u2019 den, along with their wives
        and children. The lions leaped on them and tore them apart before they even
        hit the floor of the den.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Then King Darius sent this message to the people of every race and
        nation and language throughout the world:\u201CPeace and prosperity to you!  "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "\u201CI decree that everyone throughout my kingdom should tremble
        with fear before the God of Daniel.For he is the living God,and he will endure
        forever.His kingdom will never be destroyed,and his rule will never end.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "He rescues and saves his people;he performs miraculous signs and
        wondersin the heavens and on earth.He has rescued Danielfrom the power of
        the lions.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: So Daniel prospered during the reign of Darius and the reign of Cyrus
        the Persian.[[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: '6:28 '
        content: Or <b>of Darius, that is, the reign of Cyrus the Persian.</b>
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Daniel\u2019s Vision of Four Beasts"
      title: "Daniel\u2019s Vision of Four Beasts"
      number: 1
      content: "  Earlier, during the first year of King Belshazzar\u2019s reign
        in Babylon,[[COMMENT(0)]] Daniel had a dream and saw visions as he lay in
        his bed. He wrote down the dream, and this is what he saw.  "
      comments:
      - number: '7:1 '
        content: "The first year of Belshazzar\u2019s reign (who was co-regent with
          his father, Nabonidus) was 556 <span class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>
          (or perhaps as late as 553 <span class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>)."
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'In my vision that night, I, Daniel, saw a great storm churning the
        surface of a great sea, with strong winds blowing from every direction. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Then four huge beasts came up out of the water, each different from
        the others.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "The first beast was like a lion with eagles\u2019 wings. As I watched,
        its wings were pulled off, and it was left standing with its two hind feet
        on the ground, like a human being. And it was given a human mind.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "Then I saw a second beast, and it looked like a bear. It was rearing
        up on one side, and it had three ribs in its mouth between its teeth. And
        I heard a voice saying to it, \u201CGet up! Devour the flesh of many people!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "Then the third of these strange beasts appeared, and it looked like
        a leopard. It had four bird\u2019s wings on its back, and it had four heads.
        Great authority was given to this beast.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "Then in my vision that night, I saw a fourth beast\u2014terrifying,
        dreadful, and very strong. It devoured and crushed its victims with huge
        iron teeth and trampled their remains beneath its feet. It was different
        from any of the other beasts, and it had ten horns.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'As I was looking at the horns, suddenly another small horn appeared
        among them. Three of the first horns were torn out by the roots to make room
        for it. This little horn had eyes like human eyes and a mouth that was boasting
        arrogantly.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'I watched as thrones were put in placeand the Ancient One[[COMMENT(0)]]
        sat down to judge.His clothing was as white as snow,his hair like purest
        wool.He sat on a fiery thronewith wheels of blazing fire,  '
      comments:
      - number: '7:9 '
        content: Aramaic <b>an Ancient of Days; </b>also in 7:13, 22.
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'and a river of fire was pouring out,flowing from his presence.Millions
        of angels ministered to him;many millions stood to attend him.Then the court
        began its session,and the books were opened.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "I continued to watch because I could hear the little horn\u2019s
        boastful speech. I kept watching until the fourth beast was killed and its
        body was destroyed by fire. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'The other three beasts had their authority taken from them, but they
        were allowed to live a while longer.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '7:12 '
        content: Aramaic <b>for a season and a time.</b>
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'As my vision continued that night, I saw someone like a son of man[[COMMENT(0)]]
        coming with the clouds of heaven. He approached the Ancient One and was led
        into his presence. '
      comments:
      - number: '7:13 '
        content: Or <b>like a Son of Man.</b>
    - name: '14: The Vision Is Explained'
      title: The Vision Is Explained
      number: 14
      content: "He was given authority, honor, and sovereignty over all the nations
        of the world, so that people of every race and nation and language would
        obey him. His rule is eternal\u2014it will never end. His kingdom will never
        be destroyed.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'I, Daniel, was troubled by all I had seen, and my visions terrified
        me. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'So I approached one of those standing beside the throne and asked
        him what it all meant. He explained it to me like this: '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u201CThese four huge beasts represent four kingdoms that will arise
        from the earth. "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "But in the end, the holy people of the Most High will be given the
        kingdom, and they will rule forever and ever.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'Then I wanted to know the true meaning of the fourth beast, the one
        so different from the others and so terrifying. It had devoured and crushed
        its victims with iron teeth and bronze claws, trampling their remains beneath
        its feet. '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "I also asked about the ten horns on the fourth beast\u2019s head
        and the little horn that came up afterward and destroyed three of the other
        horns. This horn had seemed greater than the others, and it had human eyes
        and a mouth that was boasting arrogantly. "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "As I watched, this horn was waging war against God\u2019s holy people
        and was defeating them, "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "until the Ancient One\u2014the Most High\u2014came and judged in
        favor of his holy people. Then the time arrived for the holy people to take
        over the kingdom.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "Then he said to me, \u201CThis fourth beast is the fourth world power
        that will rule the earth. It will be different from all the others. It will
        devour the whole world, trampling and crushing everything in its path. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'Its ten horns are ten kings who will rule that empire. Then another
        king will arise, different from the other ten, who will subdue three of them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'He will defy the Most High and oppress the holy people of the Most
        High. He will try to change their sacred festivals and laws, and they will
        be placed under his control for a time, times, and half a time.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "\u201CBut then the court will pass judgment, and all his power will
        be taken away and completely destroyed. "
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Then the sovereignty, power, and greatness of all the kingdoms under
        heaven will be given to the holy people of the Most High. His kingdom will
        last forever, and all rulers will serve and obey him.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: That was the end of the vision. I, Daniel, was terrified by my thoughts
        and my face was pale with fear, but I kept these things to myself.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Daniel\u2019s Vision of a Ram and Goat"
      title: "Daniel\u2019s Vision of a Ram and Goat"
      number: 1
      content: "    [[COMMENT(0)]]During the third year of King Belshazzar\u2019s
        reign, I, Daniel, saw another vision, following the one that had already
        appeared to me. "
      comments:
      - number: '8:1 '
        content: '  The original text from this point through chapter 12 is in Hebrew.
          See note at 2:4.  '
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'In this vision I was at the fortress of Susa, in the province of
        Elam, standing beside the Ulai River.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:2 '
        content: Or <b>the Ulai Gate; </b>also in 8:16.
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'As I looked up, I saw a ram with two long horns standing beside the
        river.[[COMMENT(0)]] One of the horns was longer than the other, even though
        it had grown later than the other one. '
      comments:
      - number: '8:3 '
        content: Or <b>the gate; </b>also in 8:6.
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'The ram butted everything out of his way to the west, to the north,
        and to the south, and no one could stand against him or help his victims.
        He did as he pleased and became very great.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "While I was watching, suddenly a male goat appeared from the west,
        crossing the land so swiftly that he didn\u2019t even touch the ground. This
        goat, which had one very large horn between its eyes, "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'headed toward the two-horned ram that I had seen standing beside
        the river, rushing at him in a rage. '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "The goat charged furiously at the ram and struck him, breaking off
        both his horns. Now the ram was helpless, and the goat knocked him down and
        trampled him. No one could rescue the ram from the goat\u2019s power.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "The goat became very powerful. But at the height of his power, his
        large horn was broken off. In the large horn\u2019s place grew four prominent
        horns pointing in the four directions of the earth. "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Then from one of the prominent horns came a small horn whose power
        grew very great. It extended toward the south and the east and toward the
        glorious land of Israel. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Its power reached to the heavens, where it attacked the heavenly
        army, throwing some of the heavenly beings and some of the stars to the ground
        and trampling them. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "It even challenged the Commander of heaven\u2019s army by canceling
        the daily sacrifices offered to him and by destroying his Temple. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'The army of heaven was restrained from responding to this rebellion.
        So the daily sacrifice was halted, and truth was overthrown. The horn succeeded
        in everything it did.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:11-12 '
        content: The meaning of the Hebrew for these verses is uncertain.
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "Then I heard two holy ones talking to each other. One of them asked,
        \u201CHow long will the events of this vision last? How long will the rebellion
        that causes desecration stop the daily sacrifices? How long will the Temple
        and heaven\u2019s army be trampled on?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: Gabriel Explains the Vision'
      title: Gabriel Explains the Vision
      number: 14
      content: "The other replied, \u201CIt will take 2,300 evenings and mornings;
        then the Temple will be made right again.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'As I, Daniel, was trying to understand the meaning of this vision,
        someone who looked like a man stood in front of me. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "And I heard a human voice calling out from the Ulai River, \u201CGabriel,
        tell this man the meaning of his vision.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "As Gabriel approached the place where I was standing, I became so
        terrified that I fell with my face to the ground. \u201CSon of man,\u201D
        he said, \u201Cyou must understand that the events you have seen in your
        vision relate to the time of the end.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'While he was speaking, I fainted and lay there with my face to the
        ground. But Gabriel roused me with a touch and helped me to my feet.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "Then he said, \u201CI am here to tell you what will happen later
        in the time of wrath. What you have seen pertains to the very end of time. "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'The two-horned ram represents the kings of Media and Persia. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'The shaggy male goat represents the king of Greece,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and the large horn between his eyes represents the first king of the Greek
        Empire. '
      comments:
      - number: '8:21 '
        content: Hebrew <b>of Javan.</b>
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'The four prominent horns that replaced the one large horn show that
        the Greek Empire will break into four kingdoms, but none as great as the
        first.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: "\u201CAt the end of their rule, when their sin is at its height,
        a fierce king, a master of intrigue, will rise to power. "
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: 'He will become very strong, but not by his own power. He will cause
        a shocking amount of destruction and succeed in everything he does. He will
        destroy powerful leaders and devastate the holy people. '
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: 'He will be a master of deception and will become arrogant; he will
        destroy many without warning. He will even take on the Prince of princes
        in battle, but he will be broken, though not by human power.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "\u201CThis vision about the 2,300 evenings and mornings[[COMMENT(0)]]
        is true. But none of these things will happen for a long time, so keep this
        vision a secret.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '8:26 '
        content: Hebrew <b>about the evenings and mornings; </b>compare 8:14.
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: Then I, Daniel, was overcome and lay sick for several days. Afterward
        I got up and performed my duties for the king, but I was greatly troubled
        by the vision and could not understand it.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Daniel\u2019s Prayer for His People"
      title: "Daniel\u2019s Prayer for His People"
      number: 1
      content: '  It was the first year of the reign of Darius the Mede, the son
        of Ahasuerus, who became king of the Babylonians.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '9:1 '
        content: Or <b>the Chaldeans.</b>
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'During the first year of his reign, I, Daniel, learned from reading
        the word of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, as revealed to Jeremiah the
        prophet, that Jerusalem must lie desolate for seventy years.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '9:2 '
        content: See Jer 25:11-12; 29:10.
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'So I turned to the Lord God and pleaded with him in prayer and fasting.
        I also wore rough burlap and sprinkled myself with ashes.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "I prayed to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> my God and confessed:\u201CO
        Lord, you are a great and awesome God! You always fulfill your covenant and
        keep your promises of unfailing love to those who love you and obey your
        commands. "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'But we have sinned and done wrong. We have rebelled against you and
        scorned your commands and regulations. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'We have refused to listen to your servants the prophets, who spoke
        on your authority to our kings and princes and ancestors and to all the people
        of the land.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "\u201CLord, you are in the right; but as you see, our faces are covered
        with shame. This is true of all of us, including the people of Judah and
        Jerusalem and all Israel, scattered near and far, wherever you have driven
        us because of our disloyalty to you. "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, we and our kings, princes, and ancestors
        are covered with shame because we have sinned against you. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'But the Lord our God is merciful and forgiving, even though we have
        rebelled against him. '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'We have not obeyed the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our God, for we
        have not followed the instructions he gave us through his servants the prophets. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "All Israel has disobeyed your instruction and turned away, refusing
        to listen to your voice.\u201CSo now the solemn curses and judgments written
        in the Law of Moses, the servant of God, have been poured down on us because
        of our sin. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'You have kept your word and done to us and our rulers exactly as
        you warned. Never has there been such a disaster as happened in Jerusalem. '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'Every curse written against us in the Law of Moses has come true.
        Yet we have refused to seek mercy from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our
        God by turning from our sins and recognizing his truth. '
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'Therefore, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has brought upon us the
        disaster he prepared. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> our God was right to
        do all of these things, for we did not obey him.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: "\u201CO Lord our God, you brought lasting honor to your name by rescuing
        your people from Egypt in a great display of power. But we have sinned and
        are full of wickedness. "
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: 'In view of all your faithful mercies, Lord, please turn your furious
        anger away from your city Jerusalem, your holy mountain. All the neighboring
        nations mock Jerusalem and your people because of our sins and the sins of
        our ancestors.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "\u201CO our God, hear your servant\u2019s prayer! Listen as I plead.
        For your own sake, Lord, smile again on your desolate sanctuary.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CO my God, lean down and listen to me. Open your eyes and see
        our despair. See how your city\u2014the city that bears your name\u2014lies
        in ruins. We make this plea, not because we deserve help, but because of
        your mercy.  "
      comments: []
    - name: "19: Gabriel\u2019s Message about the Anointed One"
      title: "Gabriel\u2019s Message about the Anointed One"
      number: 19
      content: "\u201CO Lord, hear. O Lord, forgive. O Lord, listen and act! For
        your own sake, do not delay, O my God, for your people and your city bear
        your name.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: 'I went on praying and confessing my sin and the sin of my people,
        pleading with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> my God for Jerusalem, his holy
        mountain. '
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: 'As I was praying, Gabriel, whom I had seen in the earlier vision,
        came swiftly to me at the time of the evening sacrifice. '
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: "He explained to me, \u201CDaniel, I have come here to give you insight
        and understanding. "
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'The moment you began praying, a command was given. And now I am here
        to tell you what it was, for you are very precious to God. Listen carefully
        so that you can understand the meaning of your vision.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "\u201CA period of seventy sets of seven[[COMMENT(0)]] has been decreed
        for your people and your holy city to finish their rebellion, to put an end
        to their sin, to atone for their guilt, to bring in everlasting righteousness,
        to confirm the prophetic vision, and to anoint the Most Holy Place.[[COMMENT(1)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '9:24a '
        content: Hebrew <b>seventy sevens.</b>
      - number: '9:24b '
        content: Or <b>the Most Holy One.</b>
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "Now listen and understand! Seven sets of seven plus sixty-two sets
        of seven[[COMMENT(0)]] will pass from the time the command is given to rebuild
        Jerusalem until a ruler\u2014the Anointed One[[COMMENT(1)]]\u2014comes. Jerusalem
        will be rebuilt with streets and strong defenses,[[COMMENT(2)]] despite the
        perilous times.  "
      comments:
      - number: '9:25a '
        content: Hebrew <b>Seven sevens plus sixty-two sevens.</b>
      - number: '9:25b '
        content: Or <b>an anointed one; </b>similarly in 9:26. Hebrew reads <b>a
          messiah.</b>
      - number: '9:25c '
        content: Or <b>and a moat, </b>or <b>and trenches.</b>
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: "\u201CAfter this period of sixty-two sets of seven,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        the Anointed One will be killed, appearing to have accomplished nothing,
        and a ruler will arise whose armies will destroy the city and the Temple.
        The end will come with a flood, and war and its miseries are decreed from
        that time to the very end. "
      comments:
      - number: '9:26 '
        content: Hebrew <b>After sixty-two sevens.</b>
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "The ruler will make a treaty with the people for a period of one
        set of seven,[[COMMENT(0)]] but after half this time, he will put an end
        to the sacrifices and offerings. And as a climax to all his terrible deeds,[[COMMENT(1)]]
        he will set up a sacrilegious object that causes desecration,[[COMMENT(2)]]
        until the fate decreed for this defiler is finally poured out on him.\u201D"
      comments:
      - number: '9:27a '
        content: Hebrew <b>for one seven.</b>
      - number: '9:27b '
        content: Hebrew <b>And on the wing; </b>the meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
      - number: '9:27c '
        content: Hebrew <b>an abomination of desolation.</b>
  - verses:
    - name: "1: Daniel\u2019s Vision of a Messenger"
      title: "Daniel\u2019s Vision of a Messenger"
      number: 1
      content: "  In the third year of the reign of King Cyrus of Persia,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        Daniel (also known as Belteshazzar) had another vision. He understood that
        the vision concerned events certain to happen in the future\u2014times of
        war and great hardship.  "
      comments:
      - number: '10:1 '
        content: "The third year of Cyrus\u2019s reign was 536 <span class=\"ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da\">b.c.</span>"
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'When this vision came to me, I, Daniel, had been in mourning for
        three whole weeks. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'All that time I had eaten no rich food. No meat or wine crossed my
        lips, and I used no fragrant lotions until those three weeks had passed.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: 'On April 23,[[COMMENT(0)]] as I was standing on the bank of the great
        Tigris River, '
      comments:
      - number: '10:4 '
        content: Hebrew <b>On the twenty-fourth day of the first month, </b>of the
          ancient Hebrew lunar calendar. This date in the book of Daniel can be cross-checked
          with dates in surviving Persian records and can be related accurately to
          our modern calendar. This event occurred on April 23, 536 <span class="ChapterContent_sc__Hg9da">b.c.</span>
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'I looked up and saw a man dressed in linen clothing, with a belt
        of pure gold around his waist. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: 'His body looked like a precious gem. His face flashed like lightning,
        and his eyes flamed like torches. His arms and feet shone like polished bronze,
        and his voice roared like a vast multitude of people.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'Only I, Daniel, saw this vision. The men with me saw nothing, but
        they were suddenly terrified and ran away to hide. '
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'So I was left there all alone to see this amazing vision. My strength
        left me, my face grew deathly pale, and I felt very weak. '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: 'Then I heard the man speak, and when I heard the sound of his voice,
        I fainted and lay there with my face to the ground.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Just then a hand touched me and lifted me, still trembling, to my
        hands and knees. '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "And the man said to me, \u201CDaniel, you are very precious to God,
        so listen carefully to what I have to say to you. Stand up, for I have been
        sent to you.\u201D When he said this to me, I stood up, still trembling.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: "Then he said, \u201CDon\u2019t be afraid, Daniel. Since the first
        day you began to pray for understanding and to humble yourself before your
        God, your request has been heard in heaven. I have come in answer to your
        prayer. "
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: 'But for twenty-one days the spirit prince[[COMMENT(0)]] of the kingdom
        of Persia blocked my way. Then Michael, one of the archangels,[[COMMENT(1)]]
        came to help me, and I left him there with the spirit prince of the kingdom
        of Persia.[[COMMENT(2)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '10:13a '
        content: Hebrew <b>the prince; </b>also in 10:13c, 20.
      - number: '10:13b '
        content: Hebrew <b>the chief princes.</b>
      - number: '10:13c '
        content: As in one Greek version; Hebrew reads <b>and I was left there with
          the kings of Persia. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: "Now I am here to explain what will happen to your people in the future,
        for this vision concerns a time yet to come.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'While he was speaking to me, I looked down at the ground, unable
        to say a word. '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "Then the one who looked like a man[[COMMENT(0)]] touched my lips,
        and I opened my mouth and began to speak. I said to the one standing in front
        of me, \u201CI am filled with anguish because of the vision I have seen,
        my lord, and I am very weak. "
      comments:
      - number: '10:16 '
        content: As in most manuscripts of the Masoretic Text; one manuscript of
          the Masoretic Text and one Greek version read <b>Then something that looked
          like a human hand.</b>
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: "How can someone like me, your servant, talk to you, my lord? My strength
        is gone, and I can hardly breathe.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: 'Then the one who looked like a man touched me again, and I felt my
        strength returning. '
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: "\u201CDon\u2019t be afraid,\u201D he said, \u201Cfor you are very
        precious to God. Peace! Be encouraged! Be strong!\u201DAs he spoke these
        words to me, I suddenly felt stronger and said to him, \u201CPlease speak
        to me, my lord, for you have strengthened me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "He replied, \u201CDo you know why I have come? Soon I must return
        to fight against the spirit prince of the kingdom of Persia, and after that
        the spirit prince of the kingdom of Greece[[COMMENT(0)]] will come. "
      comments:
      - number: '10:20 '
        content: Hebrew <b>of Javan.</b>
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: Meanwhile, I will tell you what is written in the Book of Truth. (No
        one helps me against these spirit princes except Michael, your spirit prince.[[COMMENT(0)]]
      comments:
      - number: '10:21 '
        content: Hebrew <b>against these except Michael, your prince.</b>
  - verses:
    - name: '1: Kings of the South and North'
      title: Kings of the South and North
      number: 1
      content: '  I have been standing beside Michael[[COMMENT(0)]] to support and
        strengthen him since the first year of the reign of Darius the Mede.)  '
      comments:
      - number: '11:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>him.</b>
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: "\u201CNow then, I will reveal the truth to you. Three more Persian
        kings will reign, to be succeeded by a fourth, far richer than the others.
        He will use his wealth to stir up everyone to fight against the kingdom of
        Greece.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '11:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>of Javan.</b>
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: "\u201CThen a mighty king will rise to power who will rule with great
        authority and accomplish everything he sets out to do. "
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "But at the height of his power, his kingdom will be broken apart
        and divided into four parts. It will not be ruled by the king\u2019s descendants,
        nor will the kingdom hold the authority it once had. For his empire will
        be uprooted and given to others.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: "\u201CThe king of the south will increase in power, but one of his
        own officials will become more powerful than he and will rule his kingdom
        with great strength.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "\u201CSome years later an alliance will be formed between the king
        of the north and the king of the south. The daughter of the king of the south
        will be given in marriage to the king of the north to secure the alliance,
        but she will lose her influence over him, and so will her father. She will
        be abandoned along with her supporters. "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: 'But when one of her relatives[[COMMENT(0)]] becomes king of the south,
        he will raise an army and enter the fortress of the king of the north and
        defeat him. '
      comments:
      - number: '11:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>a branch from her roots.</b>
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: 'When he returns to Egypt, he will carry back their idols with him,
        along with priceless articles of gold and silver. For some years afterward
        he will leave the king of the north alone.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "\u201CLater the king of the north will invade the realm of the king
        of the south but will soon return to his own land. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: "However, the sons of the king of the north will assemble a mighty
        army that will advance like a flood and carry the battle as far as the enemy\u2019s
        fortress.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CThen, in a rage, the king of the south will rally against the
        vast forces assembled by the king of the north and will defeat them. "
      comments: []
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'After the enemy army is swept away, the king of the south will be
        filled with pride and will execute many thousands of his enemies. But his
        success will be short lived.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CA few years later the king of the north will return with a
        fully equipped army far greater than before. "
      comments: []
    - name: '14: '
      title: 
      number: 14
      content: 'At that time there will be a general uprising against the king of
        the south. Violent men among your own people will join them in fulfillment
        of this vision, but they will not succeed. '
      comments: []
    - name: '15: '
      title: 
      number: 15
      content: 'Then the king of the north will come and lay siege to a fortified
        city and capture it. The best troops of the south will not be able to stand
        in the face of the onslaught.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '16: '
      title: 
      number: 16
      content: "\u201CThe king of the north will march onward unopposed; none will
        be able to stop him. He will pause in the glorious land of Israel,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        intent on destroying it. "
      comments:
      - number: '11:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the glorious land.</b>
    - name: '17: '
      title: 
      number: 17
      content: 'He will make plans to come with the might of his entire kingdom and
        will form an alliance with the king of the south. He will give him a daughter
        in marriage in order to overthrow the kingdom from within, but his plan will
        fail.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '18: '
      title: 
      number: 18
      content: "\u201CAfter this, he will turn his attention to the coastland and
        conquer many cities. But a commander from another land will put an end to
        his insolence and cause him to retreat in shame. "
      comments: []
    - name: '19: '
      title: 
      number: 19
      content: 'He will take refuge in his own fortresses but will stumble and fall
        and be seen no more.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '20: '
      title: 
      number: 20
      content: "\u201CHis successor will send out a tax collector to maintain the
        royal splendor. But after a very brief reign, he will die, though not from
        anger or in battle.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '21: '
      title: 
      number: 21
      content: "\u201CThe next to come to power will be a despicable man who is not
        in line for royal succession. He will slip in when least expected and take
        over the kingdom by flattery and intrigue. "
      comments: []
    - name: '22: '
      title: 
      number: 22
      content: 'Before him great armies will be swept away, including a covenant
        prince. '
      comments: []
    - name: '23: '
      title: 
      number: 23
      content: 'With deceitful promises, he will make various alliances. He will
        become strong despite having only a handful of followers. '
      comments: []
    - name: '24: '
      title: 
      number: 24
      content: "Without warning he will enter the richest areas of the land. Then
        he will distribute among his followers the plunder and wealth of the rich\u2014something
        his predecessors had never done. He will plot the overthrow of strongholds,
        but this will last for only a short while.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '25: '
      title: 
      number: 25
      content: "\u201CThen he will stir up his courage and raise a great army against
        the king of the south. The king of the south will go to battle with a mighty
        army, but to no avail, for there will be plots against him. "
      comments: []
    - name: '26: '
      title: 
      number: 26
      content: 'His own household will cause his downfall. His army will be swept
        away, and many will be killed. '
      comments: []
    - name: '27: '
      title: 
      number: 27
      content: "Seeking nothing but each other\u2019s harm, these kings will plot
        against each other at the conference table, attempting to deceive each other.
        But it will make no difference, for the end will come at the appointed time.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '28: '
      title: 
      number: 28
      content: "\u201CThe king of the north will then return home with great riches.
        On the way he will set himself against the people of the holy covenant, doing
        much damage before continuing his journey.  "
      comments: []
    - name: '29: '
      title: 
      number: 29
      content: "\u201CThen at the appointed time he will once again invade the south,
        but this time the result will be different. "
      comments: []
    - name: '30: '
      title: 
      number: 30
      content: 'For warships from western coastlands[[COMMENT(0)]] will scare him
        off, and he will withdraw and return home. But he will vent his anger against
        the people of the holy covenant and reward those who forsake the covenant.  '
      comments:
      - number: '11:30 '
        content: Hebrew <b>from Kittim.</b>
    - name: '31: '
      title: 
      number: 31
      content: "\u201CHis army will take over the Temple fortress, pollute the sanctuary,
        put a stop to the daily sacrifices, and set up the sacrilegious object that
        causes desecration.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '11:31 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the abomination of desolation.</b>
    - name: '32: '
      title: 
      number: 32
      content: 'He will flatter and win over those who have violated the covenant.
        But the people who know their God will be strong and will resist him.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '33: '
      title: 
      number: 33
      content: "\u201CWise leaders will give instruction to many, but these teachers
        will die by fire and sword, or they will be jailed and robbed. "
      comments: []
    - name: '34: '
      title: 
      number: 34
      content: 'During these persecutions, little help will arrive, and many who
        join them will not be sincere. '
      comments: []
    - name: '35: '
      title: 
      number: 35
      content: 'And some of the wise will fall victim to persecution. In this way,
        they will be refined and cleansed and made pure until the time of the end,
        for the appointed time is still to come.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '36: '
      title: 
      number: 36
      content: "\u201CThe king will do as he pleases, exalting himself and claiming
        to be greater than every god, even blaspheming the God of gods. He will succeed,
        but only until the time of wrath is completed. For what has been determined
        will surely take place. "
      comments: []
    - name: '37: '
      title: 
      number: 37
      content: 'He will have no respect for the gods of his ancestors, or for the
        god loved by women, or for any other god, for he will boast that he is greater
        than them all. '
      comments: []
    - name: '38: '
      title: 
      number: 38
      content: "Instead of these, he will worship the god of fortresses\u2014a god
        his ancestors never knew\u2014and lavish on him gold, silver, precious stones,
        and expensive gifts. "
      comments: []
    - name: '39: '
      title: 
      number: 39
      content: "Claiming this foreign god\u2019s help, he will attack the strongest
        fortresses. He will honor those who submit to him, appointing them to positions
        of authority and dividing the land among them as their reward.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '11:39 '
        content: Or <b>at a price.</b>
    - name: '40: '
      title: 
      number: 40
      content: "\u201CThen at the time of the end, the king of the south will attack
        the king of the north. The king of the north will storm out with chariots,
        charioteers, and a vast navy. He will invade various lands and sweep through
        them like a flood. "
      comments: []
    - name: '41: '
      title: 
      number: 41
      content: 'He will enter the glorious land of Israel,[[COMMENT(0)]] and many
        nations will fall, but Moab, Edom, and the best part of Ammon will escape. '
      comments:
      - number: '11:41 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the glorious land.</b>
    - name: '42: '
      title: 
      number: 42
      content: 'He will conquer many countries, and even Egypt will not escape. '
      comments: []
    - name: '43: '
      title: 
      number: 43
      content: 'He will gain control over the gold, silver, and treasures of Egypt,
        and the Libyans and Ethiopians[[COMMENT(0)]] will be his servants.  '
      comments:
      - number: '11:43 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Cushites.</b>
    - name: '44: '
      title: 
      number: 44
      content: "\u201CBut then news from the east and the north will alarm him, and
        he will set out in great anger to destroy and obliterate many. "
      comments: []
    - name: '45: '
      title: 
      number: 45
      content: He will stop between the glorious holy mountain and the sea and will
        pitch his royal tents. But while he is there, his time will suddenly run
        out, and no one will help him.
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - name: '1: The Time of the End'
      title: The Time of the End
      number: 1
      content: "  \u201CAt that time Michael, the archangel[[COMMENT(0)]] who stands
        guard over your nation, will arise. Then there will be a time of anguish
        greater than any since nations first came into existence. But at that time
        every one of your people whose name is written in the book will be rescued. "
      comments:
      - number: '12:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the great prince.</b>
    - name: '2: '
      title: 
      number: 2
      content: 'Many of those whose bodies lie dead and buried will rise up, some
        to everlasting life and some to shame and everlasting disgrace. '
      comments: []
    - name: '3: '
      title: 
      number: 3
      content: 'Those who are wise will shine as bright as the sky, and those who
        lead many to righteousness will shine like the stars forever. '
      comments: []
    - name: '4: '
      title: 
      number: 4
      content: "But you, Daniel, keep this prophecy a secret; seal up the book until
        the time of the end, when many will rush here and there, and knowledge will
        increase.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '5: '
      title: 
      number: 5
      content: 'Then I, Daniel, looked and saw two others standing on opposite banks
        of the river. '
      comments: []
    - name: '6: '
      title: 
      number: 6
      content: "One of them asked the man dressed in linen, who was now standing
        above the river, \u201CHow long will it be until these shocking events are
        over?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '7: '
      title: 
      number: 7
      content: "The man dressed in linen, who was standing above the river, raised
        both his hands toward heaven and took a solemn oath by the One who lives
        forever, saying, \u201CIt will go on for a time, times, and half a time.
        When the shattering of the holy people has finally come to an end, all these
        things will have happened.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '8: '
      title: 
      number: 8
      content: "I heard what he said, but I did not understand what he meant. So
        I asked, \u201CHow will all this finally end, my lord?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - name: '9: '
      title: 
      number: 9
      content: "But he said, \u201CGo now, Daniel, for what I have said is kept secret
        and sealed until the time of the end. "
      comments: []
    - name: '10: '
      title: 
      number: 10
      content: 'Many will be purified, cleansed, and refined by these trials. But
        the wicked will continue in their wickedness, and none of them will understand.
        Only those who are wise will know what it means.  '
      comments: []
    - name: '11: '
      title: 
      number: 11
      content: "\u201CFrom the time the daily sacrifice is stopped and the sacrilegious
        object that causes desecration[[COMMENT(0)]] is set up to be worshiped, there
        will be 1,290 days. "
      comments:
      - number: '12:11 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the abomination of desolation.</b>
    - name: '12: '
      title: 
      number: 12
      content: 'And blessed are those who wait and remain until the end of the 1,335
        days!  '
      comments: []
    - name: '13: '
      title: 
      number: 13
      content: "\u201CAs for you, go your way until the end. You will rest, and then
        at the end of the days, you will rise again to receive the inheritance set
        aside for you.\u201D"
      comments: []
